<DOC><DOCNO> AP891010-0193 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-89 2218EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Britain-SAfrica     10-10 0267</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Britain-SAfrica,0274</SECOND><HEAD>Thatcher Welcomes Release of South African Prisoners</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-SAfrica-Prisoners</HEAD><DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher onTuesday welcomed the release of eight top-security politicalprisoners in South Africa as ``a major step in the rightdirection.''   Mrs. Thatcher, attending the first day of the annual conferenceof her governing Conservative Party, said: ``Naturally we all hopethat it will lead on to the release of Nelson Mandela and open theway for negotiations on a new constitution for South Africa.''   The announcement of the release, on South Africa's statetelevision, said discussions had been held with Mandela and he had``confirmed again his own release is not now on the agenda.'' Amongthose freed was his close friend, Walter Sisulu, 77,secretary-general of the ANC from 1949-54.   ``It is a major step in the right direction,'' Mrs. Thatchersaid.   South African President F.W. de Klerk telephoned the primeminister in Blackpool before the official announcment was made,aides said.   British government sources, quoted by the domestic news agencyPress Association, said the announcment justified Mrs. Thatcher'sopposition to tough economic sanctions against South Africa. Shehas favored maintaining contact with Pretoria as a means of pushingfor negotiated reforms in South Africa.   Opposition Labor Party leader Neil Kinnock also welcomed deKlerk's announcement. ``If it is true _ this is great news and manywill want to give tribute to Walter Sisulu for his strength andcourage in all these years in prison.   ``Surely now the unconditional release of Nelson Mandela and allother political prisoners in South Africa cannot be delayed.''</TEXT></DOC>